node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text: We're back with another episode of AD Visits, and today, we're taking you to Hudson Yards to see the home of fashion designer @brian_atwood and husband @drjakedeutsch. With photography on every wall and incredible city views 64 stories above Manhattan, explore their high-rise artistic aerie. Cover photo by @twilliamsphoto.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 19, 2021. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
When designing her L.A. home, model @jesshart would text designer Carlos Mota (@casamotachic) photos of furniture she found online, and he’d weigh in. When it wasn’t yet safe for contractors to come back to work, Hart's fiancé @jameskirkham built the closet cabinetry, painted rooms, and rewired lights. He even learned to weld, thanks to the equipment at his body shop and instructional YouTube videos, building an iron gate that’s seven feet tall for their yard. “I felt like he did just as much as the contractors eventually did,” says Hart. “It all kept coming together one step at a time.”

Tour the colorful home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @casamotachic; words by @carly_olson.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 19, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
“I wanted you to feel like you were walking into Zen,” says designer Noha Hassan (@nohahassandesigns) of this NYC apartment's oversized bedroom suite, which occupies the whole top floor of the apartment. “The injection of color is meant to be inviting and relaxing as well, because everything else is monochromatic.”

Explore the sky-high home at our bio link. Photo by @frankoudeman; design by @nohahassandesigns; words by @arielfoxman.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 19, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
“He wanted light and color and freshness,” says #AD100 designer @indiamahdavi says of the homeowner of this project in the South of France “I think that’s why he chose me.”

Step inside the light-filled getaway at our bio link. Photo by Vincent Leroux; design by @indiamahdavi; words by @samedford.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 18, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
"Functionality is always key when designing a space; you can design the most beautiful room in the world, but if it doesn't work for how the clients live, that's not a win in my book. So, making sure that every room is thoughtfully executed in line with a client's specific needs and lifestyle is always very crucial." —designer @arielokin

Tour the Upper East Side home she designed at our bio link. Photo by @donnadotanphoto; design by @arielokin; words by Lauren Jones.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 18, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text:
“This is definitely not a sun-worshipping beach house,” says designer Vanessa Alexander (@alexanderdesignbuild) of the third Malibu home that she and Steve, a Hollywood agent, have built together. That figure includes residences in the celebrity shoreline enclave of Point Dume and the gated waterfront community of Serra Retreat. “We don’t see the ocean from here. Instead, we see mountains and big trees, but the most remarkable part about this landscape is the painterly quality of the light.”

Step inside the beautiful spaces at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @rowelosangeles; design by @alexanderdesignbuild; words by @leilanimarielabong.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 18, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
For his 1970s Edward Fickett home, designer @philippenaouri selected furnishings that qualify as art but beg to be used: chairs by Charles and Ray Eames and Le Corbusier, a sofa by Mies Van Der Rohe, a lamp by Torchiere. The art runs the gamut from Alexander Calder and Robert Chuey to @mrbrainwash, a close friend of Naouri’s. “I put his portrait of Jimi Hendrix in the living room to give it that ’60s feeling,” he says. “This was the last house of Fickett’s that had that ’60s vibe.”

Explore the retro home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @philippenaouri; words by @sheilaym.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 17, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Rather than relying on flashy gimmicks, the office of Jay-Z's @rocnation gathers strength from its deep sense of materiality, expressed in the chunky marble counters that anchor the central meeting/dining/entertainment zone, in the bespoke benches and serpentine banquettes of muscular concrete, and, perhaps most noticeably, in the columns and accent walls sheathed in a pebbly lime plaster aggregate. “The mixture is a nod to where I grew up. Montreal modernism is wrapped up in the texture and aesthetic of concrete—a combination of brutalism and beauty,” designer @willoperron observes.

Tour Roc Nation's sophisticated offices at our bio link. Photo by @shadedeggesphotography; styling by @emilyedithbowser; design by @willoperron; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 17, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
“We wanted to capture prewar elegance and postwar modernity,” Katherine Newman (@katherinenewmandesign) says of this historic Toronto home. In addition to sourcing furniture and carefully scaling everything to each room’s individual dimensions, her firm designed custom pieces “inspired by French, Danish, and Italian midcentury designers, with a focus on furniture as art.” The resulting collection was fabricated by artisans from all over the world.

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @virginmacdonald; design by @katherinenewmandesign; words by Katie Chang.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and standing.

node.text:
On the 28th floor of 4 World Trade Center (@wtc), there is a constant play of light as sun bounces off the surrounding Manhattan glass towers and Hudson River. “I’ve really developed a relationship with these buildings,” says artist @maryamturkey, whose latest creations reveal the influence of those shadows and reflections. Working out of the space as part of the Silver Art Projects residency program for the past year, the Pratt graduate, who came to the U.S. from Iraq as a refugee in 2009, has drawn connections between the countries she’s called home.

Meet AD's newest "one to watch" at our bio link. Photo by @simbarashecha; words by @_h_mart_.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 16, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
“Bravery in style comes from combinations like that,” interior decorator @rachelchudley observes about a flowered chintz sofa amid Le Corbusier chairs. “That’s why this was such a creatively thrilling project for me. The sofa needed to be combined with something that had an edge so it didn’t look like some old-school object on display.” Helping with that blending is the plant-filled light well—mirrored to increase both the sunlight and the foliage—a grand old Turkish carpet, and an object that neither homeowner ever felt that they would own: an antique wall-spanning tapestry depicting a pastoral scene populated by sheep.

Tour the London townhouse at our bio link. Photo by @simonuptonphotos; styling by @saramathersstylist; design by @rachelchudley; words by @mrmitchowens.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 16, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
For a finishing touch, at the client’s request, #AD100 designer @luislaplace created three water features, so the Mexican home would link to the ocean, like a river flowing to the sea. One, a low black-stone cylinder on the terrace, awash with smooth water, was a riff on the glass sculptures of American artist Roni Horn. Another, a stone canal, serenely pours into the infinity pool. As Laplace points out, “fountains are a recurrent element of Mexican architecture, and water is very soothing.”

Explore the home from our October cover at our bio link. Photo by @fernandomarroquint; styling by Mariana Estrada; design by @luislaplace; words by @danathomasparis.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 16, 2021. May be an image of table and living room.

node.text:
“In the beginning he didn’t want to be too bold,” #AD100 designer @indiamahdavi says of her client and his home in the South of France. “But the house was built in stages, not all at once. I told him we needed something strong to bring it together and give it character.”

Explore the colorful home at our bio link. Photo by Vincent Leroux; design by @indiamahdavi; words by @samedford.
